@indyjay1969 The 8th September 1966 was the date the show first aired on NBC, with the episode ‘The Man Trap.’ This was the third episode filmed, but the first to be broadcast in America.

In the UK the BBC didn’t buy the rights until some years later and the first episode on BBC One, shown on the  12th July 1969, was ‘Where No Man Has Gone Before.’ (This was aired on NBC as episode three, was the second pilot produced - after The Cage - and the first to feature William Shatner as Kirk.)

I hope that clears up any confusion.

@loristraylit1827 Mens sana in corpore sano. You could excuse the odd big person in Old Trek, especially since a minute fraction of them actually served in Starfleet, and then again were meant to signify people who weren't serving on the front lines at the beginning of a career -- as opposed to people, it seems, *who choose to be fat* despite the need to be in fairly healthy physical shape to help them survive, but others depending on them as well. 

These characters also clearly are not the best and brightest. There's no stricture or standard or failure line being applied here. Canonically, members of Starfleet had quite a reputation attached to their station. They were seen as a shining example because when all else failed, they could be relied upon to remember their training and the competencies they've built. It is clear within the first few moments that this is a Starfleet that has lowered it's standards to the point where membership is meaningless. Like the idol worship of the fatted calf, it's a gesture void of sacrifice, conviction, or personal quest.

I'm a big person myself -- but even I have trouble imagining a scenario where I play a hero that has to rescue people I care about from cramped naval compartments that are on fire, or ruptured and flooding with water. And it is the same with these actors - How many of them could you imagine crawling through tens of meters of Jeffries Tubes? How many of them could carry a comrade away from phaser fire? How many of them could you trust to man their post despite low morale, confusion, or doubt?
